            {
               "text": "### Bantu Expansion\n\nWhen studying the languages spoken on the African continent, it is noteworthy that linguistic diversity, despite the vast territorial expanse, is lower compared to that of the Americas (*Abya Yala*) and Asia (<htcite0>; <htcite1>).\n\nThis fact leads us to conclude that there was an expansion of the Bantu people into different regions of Africa (<htcite2>).\n\n#### Expansion Models\n\nThe figure in this section presents two possible hypotheses for the Bantu migration (<htcite3>; <htcite4>):\n- **Early-split**: the Bantu migration occurs in two directions—east and west of the African continent.\n- **Late-split**: in this hypothesis, the Bantu dispersal would have occurred only after crossing the rainforests.\n\nSince sciences are developed through questioning and evidence, not just theories, the foundations supporting this model are not considered immutable. This fact led Doctor Igor Yanovich to raise some points, which we address next (<htcite5>).\n\n#### A Linguistic Perspective\n\nOne of the first points addressed by Igor Yanovich regarding the Bantu languages concerns their current classification. He draws attention to the fact that the 540 currently classified languages follow a classificatory system that should not be understood as a definitive scientific consensus (<htcite6>; <htcite7>).",
               "source": [
                  {
                     "type": 1,
                     "uuid": "baffbb52-eb8f-41ee-8842-91b89ae393bb",
                     "text": "Bostoen, K.",
                     "page": "pp. 227",
                     "date_time": {
                        "type": "gregory",
                        "year": "2018",
                        "month": "",
                        "day": ""
