               "PostMention": ""
            },
            {
               "text": "Another point highlighted by Igor Yanovich is related to the possible origin of the Bantu languages' expansion from Cameroon, between approximately <htdate0> and <htdate1>, a hypothesis that lacks sufficient data for robust support (<htcite0>; <htcite1>; <htcite2>).\n\nRegarding the tree that would connect the Bantu languages, Igor Yanovich raised points that require deeper analysis, such as the small amount of data analyzed and the fact that the connection between the languages may not be unidirectional, but could actually be convergent, as occurs in some genealogical analyses (<htcite3>).\n\n#### Archaeology\n\nArchaeological research in Africa, especially in the central region, is still in its early stages, with few sites having been explored. Furthermore, the African soil does not favor the preservation of artifacts over millennia. As a consequence, there is no clear evidence regarding the complete evolution of pottery artifacts (<htcite4>).",
               "source": [
                  {
                     "type": 1,
                     "uuid": "baffbb52-eb8f-41ee-8842-91b89ae393bb",
                     "text": "Bostoen, K.",
                     "page": "pp. 228",
                     "date_time": {
                        "type": "gregory",
                        "year": "2018",
                        "month": "",
