            {
               "text": "<center><div class=\"first_steps_reflection_parent\"><div class=\"first_steps_reflection question_mark\"><i class=\"fa-solid fa-brain\"></i></div><div class=\"first_steps_reflection\"><b>Reflection: On the Lack of Evidence</b><br /><br />\"The absence of evidence is not evidence of absence\" (<htcite0>) is a conclusion presented by different researchers over a century ago.<br /><br />The observations regarding the scarcity of data made by Dr. Igor Yanovich cannot be ignored. However, considering the understanding of “absence of evidence” presented at the beginning of this reflection, do you consider these observations sufficient to completely dismiss the current understanding of the dispersal into two possible routes?</div></div></center></p>",
               "source": [
                  {
                     "type": 1,
                     "uuid": "95106e43-ec63-4b00-9852-ce703b0d8a78",
                     "text": "Wright, William",
                     "page": "pp. 59",
                     "date_time": {
                        "type": "gregory",
                        "year": "1888",
                        "month": "",
                        "day": ""
                     }
                  }
               ],
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "html",
               "PostMention": ""
            },
            {
               "text": "#### Genetics\n\nRegarding genetics, Igor Yanovich again draws attention to the fact that it is only in recent years that genetic data has begun to be better collected and studied in Sub-Saharan Africa (<htcite0>). In general, genetic studies have been confirming the models previously proposed (<htcite1>; <htcite2>; <htcite3>).\n\n#### Final Reflection\n\nIn this text, we have explored the expansion of the Bantu people from a perspective different from that already addressed in the genealogy section (<htcite4>).\n\nOne of the pieces of information presented here—and not explored in the genealogy section—is the existence of more than 500 different languages originating from the Bantu people (<htcite5>). Based on this fact, we propose the following final reflection:",
               "source": [
                  {
                     "type": 1,
                     "uuid": "5f55c3fc-d434-4d56-a6fc-838649b8aa97",
                     "text": "Yanovich, I.",
